DS220 Final Project¶

My main goal when analyzing this data is to determine what affects winning percentage in baseball the most. In order to do so, I am focusing on one specific team, the San Diego Padres in order to limit other factors that could come into play.¶

Questions:¶

How is OPS related to wins?¶

How much can OPS vary for a certain number of wins?¶

How is ERA related to wins?¶

How much can ERA vary for a certain number of wins?¶

How are OPS and ERA related?¶

Have the OPS trends changed overtime?¶

Have the ERA trends changed overtime?¶

Do left or right handed batters perform better?¶

Do left or right handed pitchers perform better?¶

The first two data sets were gathered from Kaggle.Com. The third data set was gathered from baeballrefernce.com.

How is OPS related to wins?¶

The first step here is to eliminate the specific players and focus soley on the team's stats over each year. In order to use one specific statistic to measure the team's success, we will use "On Base Plus Slugging Percentage" or "OPS". OPS is a measurement of the average amount of bases a player gets per at bat. The higher the OPS, the better the team is doing offensively.

In [15]:
batting_year=data_batting.groupby('Year')['On_Base_Plus_Slugging_Percentage'].mean().reset_index()
batting_year.head()
Out[15]:
Year On_Base_Plus_Slugging_Percentage
0 1969 0.456167
1 1970 0.456649
2 1971 0.506500
3 1972 0.408073
4 1973 0.468062

The next step after we have grouped the batting data by year to get the average OPS by year, is merging the table with the wins per year table using a left join. This allows us to see how many wins the team got per season, which we can then use to compare OPS and wins in the future.

In [16]:
batting_wins_year = pd.merge(batting_year, wins_year, on='Year', how='left')
batting_wins_year.head()[["Year","On_Base_Plus_Slugging_Percentage","W"]]
Out[16]:
Year On_Base_Plus_Slugging_Percentage W

1 1970 0.456649 63
2 1971 0.506500 61
3 1972 0.408073 58
4 1973 0.468062 60

Now to analyze how OPS affects winning, we can graph the OPS of each year against the wins of each year. When looking at the scatter plot initially, there is not much to see. Therefore, we can add a line of best fit to really see how OPS affects how many games a team will win. Looking at this line, we see that it is basically horizontal, meaning that no matter the OPS of the wins are not greatly affected.

In [131]:

How much can OPS vary for a certain number of wins?¶

Since the previous graphs did not show much correlation between wins and OPS, we can now create a box plot to see how much the OPS can vary for seasons with the same win totals. With this boxplot we are able to see that the majority of wins are grouped between 68 and 82 wins, just below average for a 162 game season. We can also see that the OPS for a team can vary greatly for the same win total. For example, for the seasons they won 75 games, the OPS has been as low as 0.34, but as high as 0.53, a very large difference.

In [132]:

plt.ylabel('On Base Plus Slugging')

plt.gca().spines['right'].set_visible(False)
plt.show()

How is ERA related to wins?¶

Once again we are grouping the data by year, but this time we are using the pitching data. Now because we are focusing on pitching this time, we cannot use OPS, instead we use "Earned Run Average" or ERA. ERA represents the average number of runs a pitcher allows per 9 innings, so we will use this as our main defensive statistic.

In [18]:
pitching_year=data_pitching.groupby('Year')['Earned_Run_Average'].mean().reset_index()
pitching_year.head()
Out[18]:

1 1970 5.646875

3 1972 4.851333
4 1973 4.155000

Next, we again have to join our table with the wins per pear. We use a left join again on the year columns, and now we can compare ERA with Wins in order to see if there is an apparent correlation.

However, once again, no relationship is readily available, so we must create a line of best fit. With the line of best fit added, we can see that there is downward slope. This means that the lower the team's ERA is, the more likely the team is to win more games, or that the team will allow fewer runs. This makes sense.

How much can ERA vary for a certain number of wins?¶

Once again we can check how much the ERA varies for each season of the same winning total. With this boxplot, the data is still grouped about the same area of 68 to 82 wins which makes sense. If we then look closer, the highs and lows of ther ERA tend to vary less than OPS did in the previous boxplot. With this information we can tell that ERA is generally a better statistic to look at for predicting the win total for a season.

Are OPS and ERA related?¶

Now, to see if OPS and ERA are related, we can peform a left join by year on both the batting_year, and pitching_year dataframes. Since these dataframes are already grouped by year, no more grouping has to be done.

In [55]:
batting_pitching=pd.merge(batting_year,pitching_year, on="Year",how="left")
batting_pitching.head(5)[["Year","Earned_Run_Average","On_Base_Plus_Slugging_Percentage"]]
Out[55]:
Year Earned_Run_Average On_Base_Plus_Slugging_Percentage
0 1969 5.180000 0.456167
1 1970 5.646875 0.456649
2 1971 3.555000 0.506500
3 1972 4.851333 0.408073
4 1973 4.155000 0.468062

Now that we have these two dataframes joined together by year, we can create another scatterplot, this time with ERA on the X axis, and OPS on the Y axis. If we introduce a line of best fit we can see that the higher the OPS, the more likely the team is to have a lower ERA. While batting and pitching tend to be independent of one another in baseball, this apparent correlation could be due to a number of factors. One such example is that if a team already has a low OPS or high ERA, the less likely they are to focus on winning, leading the other stat to fall as well. Another possibility could be due to salary. If a team is not spending much money on hitters, leading to them having a low OPS, it is more likely they will spend less money on pitchers thus leading to them having a high ERA.

Have the OPS trends changed overtime?¶

Next we want to see how these trends have changed over the years regarding the Padres. In order to see this, we will first split up the batting_wins_data set into two sections, the first half of the Padres existence, and the second half. In order to find this, we will start at the inception year, 1969, and then add half of the total years the team has existed to find the total range. This creates the first half group of years.

In [24]:
Year_Range=[1969,1969+56/2]
batting_first_half=batting_wins_year[batting_wins_year['Year'].isin(range(1969,int(1969+56/2)))]
batting_first_half.head(2)

Conclusions:¶

Overall, looking at the datasets and the resulting graphics, we were able to make a few conclusions.
When thinking about whether OPS was related to wins, we were able to see that no matter the OPS, wins were generally unaffected. Then when looking at how much OPS can vary for certain number of wins we came to a similar conclusion, as OPS could vary greatly with the same win total.

When looking at the relationship between ERA and Wins, we saw that the lower the ERA of a team was, the more likely they were to win more games. Then when we looked at how much the ERA could vary at a specific win count, we saw that there was still variation, but to a much lower extent than OPS.

When we questioned if ERA and OPS were related, we saw what that a higher ERA seemed to predict a lower OPS, however we questioned this result as there may have been other factors affecting this result.

Looking at whether OPS vs Wins and ERA vs Wins had changed overtime, we were able to see that in the second half of the Padres' existence, a higher ERA has become more related to a higher number of wins, while the relationship between ERA and Wins has mostly stayed the same.

Finally, when looking at the performance of right handed batters and pitcher versus left handed batters and pitchers we were able to see that left handed batters more often hit for a higher OPS, with a higher maxmimum OPS. Looking at the pitchers side of things, left handed pitchers tended to have a much larger range of what ERA with a large variation, however they had a high peak at a low ERA, making them more likely to throw a very low ERA compared to right handers.
